[SPEAKER_08]: All right, so I say yes too, so that's approved.

369
00:33:24,228 --> 00:33:24,829
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you all.

370
00:33:25,649 --> 00:33:28,472
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's go back to the next agenda.

371
00:33:30,493 --> 00:33:35,957
[SPEAKER_08]: And now we can talk about the next thing on the agenda, which is CanMETRID Apply.

372
00:33:36,858 --> 00:33:45,707
[SPEAKER_08]: And if so, should Medford apply to be one of the 10 cities in the Massachusetts pilot program that bans the use of fossil fuels in new buildings and major renovations?

373
00:33:45,767 --> 00:33:48,089
[SPEAKER_08]: So that's up for discussion for all.

374
00:33:48,129 --> 00:33:53,735
[SPEAKER_08]: So I would appreciate anyone to start the discussion.

375
00:33:55,132 --> 00:33:57,253
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, I just want to clarify, because that's my item.

376
00:33:57,353 --> 00:34:02,897
[SPEAKER_04]: So that was more a question for Alicia, because I didn't know whether it's still possible to apply.

377
00:34:02,997 --> 00:34:04,678
[SPEAKER_04]: I know that Boston applied late.

378
00:34:05,818 --> 00:34:11,822
[SPEAKER_04]: And I tried to look this up online to see whether I could find any information to see whether cities can still apply.

379
00:34:12,222 --> 00:34:13,323
[SPEAKER_04]: And I couldn't find anything.

380
00:34:13,443 --> 00:34:17,965
[SPEAKER_04]: So I mean, maybe we cannot apply, and then this is a discussion that has no point.

381
00:34:18,025 --> 00:34:18,426
[SPEAKER_04]: But yeah.

382
00:34:22,557 --> 00:34:34,787
[SPEAKER_00]: I will say that it was my understanding when that went in front of the state, that the law was actually listed 10 specific communities that were being approved to do it.

383
00:34:35,307 --> 00:34:50,339
[SPEAKER_00]: There were 10 that had petitioned the state for that policy, and that Boston and someone else were both trying to say, if one of those 10 drop out,

384
00:34:50,954 --> 00:34:54,015
[SPEAKER_00]: can we then fill that slot?

385
00:34:54,415 --> 00:34:56,876
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, if somebody knows differently than I, that's fine.

386
00:34:56,916 --> 00:35:01,678
[SPEAKER_00]: I didn't get a chance to look this one up, but that was my understanding of it.

387
00:35:03,218 --> 00:35:12,321
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so according to what I read in the Boston Globe, then it was still, then this, I think it was back from August, if I remember correctly.

388
00:35:12,361 --> 00:35:20,724
[SPEAKER_04]: And then it was still not clear whether the 10 communities were gonna satisfy the public housing requirement that they have.

389
00:35:21,205 --> 00:35:22,568
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think it was up in the air.

390
00:35:24,691 --> 00:35:25,773
[SPEAKER_00]: I will tell you that.

391
00:35:26,999 --> 00:35:29,921
[SPEAKER_00]: There are a lot of things that people say will stifle development.

392
00:35:30,742 --> 00:35:32,544
[SPEAKER_00]: Medford is not ready to do this.

393
00:35:33,544 --> 00:35:40,991
[SPEAKER_00]: It would actually cause a lot of trouble for a lot of our developers if we put that moratorium on immediately.

394
00:35:42,112 --> 00:35:51,940
[SPEAKER_00]: One of the things that we have found to work well is to let Boston and Cambridge, sometimes Brookline, take the lead on these very progressive things.

395
00:35:52,578 --> 00:35:54,339
[SPEAKER_00]: then they get the company's used to it.

396
00:35:55,080 --> 00:36:07,888
[SPEAKER_00]: And then when we say, oh, we're doing it too, they're like, fine, we already know how to do it, we do it in Cambridge, like we can do it, but let them sort of set the pace first, because a company will pay anything practically to build in Cambridge.

397
00:36:08,728 --> 00:36:09,988
[SPEAKER_00]: and sometimes in Boston.

398
00:36:11,048 --> 00:36:20,330
[SPEAKER_00]: So this is sort of, rather than us, if we put in rules that companies don't like, they say, fine, we'll go to Malden or Woburn.

399
00:36:20,970 --> 00:36:22,631
[SPEAKER_00]: We'll just go one city further.

400
00:36:23,831 --> 00:36:31,832
[SPEAKER_00]: So I feel like this one is too aggressive for Medford at this point.

401
00:36:32,492 --> 00:36:35,473
[SPEAKER_00]: Not that we wouldn't do it, but not first.

402
00:36:37,283 --> 00:36:38,443
[SPEAKER_00]: I see Luke has his hand up.

403
00:36:38,503 --> 00:36:41,764
[SPEAKER_00]: I know he's really in the middle of this energy stuff.

404
00:36:41,824 --> 00:36:53,748
[SPEAKER_10]: I did also just want to point out that, so in a recent Built Environment Plus webinar, an excellent group that is really pushing

405
00:36:54,608 --> 00:36:56,530
[SPEAKER_10]: net zero and electrification.

406
00:36:56,550 --> 00:37:18,568
[SPEAKER_10]: An engineering company that is doing a lot of net zero buildings, a lot of extremely high performance buildings, presented a slide that literally showed dozens of buildings and compared to looking in Boston in particular,

407
00:37:20,650 --> 00:37:44,748
[SPEAKER_10]: and you know the average building is using like more than half of their energy comes from gas and about less than half from electric and pushing for electrification as many of the new higher performance buildings are doing they are able to get very close to and they have I mean I could share this slide if I can

408
00:37:46,770 --> 00:38:04,901
[SPEAKER_10]: share screen, but essentially with ground and air source heat pumps, as well as exhaust heat pump for labs, they're able to get extremely close to net zero with electric, but they very often need a very small amount of gas for those peak loads.

409
00:38:05,561 --> 00:38:07,943
[SPEAKER_10]: And not having that is a big deal.

410
00:38:09,484 --> 00:38:18,591
[SPEAKER_10]: And it's a big deal in terms of the size of the equipment that you then need to buy in order to meet those few peak moments.

411
00:38:20,192 --> 00:38:24,035
[SPEAKER_10]: And that means that it's oversized for the rest of the year.

412
00:38:24,816 --> 00:38:37,005
[SPEAKER_10]: So in these cases, it's clearly showing that it is more cost effective and frankly, more energy effective to at least have the option to have some gas for those peak conditions.

413
00:38:41,062 --> 00:38:41,282
[SPEAKER_02]: Thanks.

414
00:38:44,123 --> 00:38:44,523
[SPEAKER_02]: Excellent.

415
00:38:46,744 --> 00:38:47,765
[SPEAKER_08]: Any other comments on this?

416
00:38:48,905 --> 00:38:51,206
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, I have my hand up.

417
00:38:52,226 --> 00:38:53,187
[SPEAKER_05]: So I'll speak.

418
00:38:55,108 --> 00:39:00,110
[SPEAKER_05]: I support what Alicia and Luke have just said.

419
00:39:00,190 --> 00:39:04,011
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that going to the new stretch code is an excellent thing.

420
00:39:04,051 --> 00:39:08,393
[SPEAKER_05]: And Medford is apparently doing that to go to

421
00:39:09,378 --> 00:39:21,367
[SPEAKER_05]: Complete net zero, I think, is a leap too far for us right now for the reasons Alicia outlined, and we very much need development.

422
00:39:22,407 --> 00:39:23,949
[SPEAKER_05]: We very much need building.

423
00:39:24,849 --> 00:39:25,790
[SPEAKER_05]: We need housing.

424
00:39:26,615 --> 00:39:27,875
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, we need mixed use.

425
00:39:28,796 --> 00:39:41,899
[SPEAKER_05]: I would just not like to see us discourage responsible energy efficient development by making the rules so tight that developers feel they have to go elsewhere.

426
00:39:41,919 --> 00:39:48,241
[SPEAKER_08]: So what timeline do you imagine for this to be?

427
00:39:49,641 --> 00:39:52,262
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm not obviously trying to

428
00:39:54,580 --> 00:40:05,456
[SPEAKER_08]: pigeonhole anyone in this, but what timeline do you think we need to sort of mix and match?

429
00:40:05,916 --> 00:40:09,662
[SPEAKER_08]: How far in the future do you think we can mix and match?

430
00:40:10,420 --> 00:40:31,340
[SPEAKER_10]: Martha may have some more comments on that, but I would just add that we have a three-year code cycle and a three-year energy cycle for our utility renewable energy and energy efficiency planning.

431
00:40:33,162 --> 00:40:43,750
[SPEAKER_10]: And the new code is geared to establish these rules and then be able to be ratcheted down.

432
00:40:43,770 --> 00:40:47,313
[SPEAKER_10]: And that is something that can happen every three years.

433
00:40:47,373 --> 00:40:53,818
[SPEAKER_10]: And if in three years, it looks like, you know, we're making progress, then we can tighten things up.

434
00:40:55,239 --> 00:41:04,305
[SPEAKER_10]: So three years is a long time, but in terms of a building, I mean, it takes three years to plan and start construction on a building sometimes.

435
00:41:05,226 --> 00:41:18,055
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, and we can't, I mean, I'm just asking the question, we can't imagine a situation where that could be accelerated in any way.

436
00:41:22,417 --> 00:41:31,443
[SPEAKER_10]: I think it's possible, but as I've said before, and I say often to friends, you can't skip the necessary steps to success.

437
00:41:31,983 --> 00:41:38,027
[SPEAKER_10]: And if you would like to succeed, if you skip past them, then you won't.

438
00:41:38,368 --> 00:41:48,755
[SPEAKER_10]: So yeah, we kind of need to do what works first and make sure that it works well and get people up to speed.

439
00:41:49,315 --> 00:41:50,356
[SPEAKER_10]: If the contractors are,

440
00:41:51,156 --> 00:41:55,317
[SPEAKER_10]: not doing it and the developers are not doing it because they can get away with it.

441
00:41:55,737 --> 00:42:02,999
[SPEAKER_10]: And because they, you know, can argue that it's, it's impossible, then it won't happen.

442
00:42:04,199 --> 00:42:07,420
[SPEAKER_00]: One thing, sorry, I don't want to jump in, but I, I do have to run.

443
00:42:07,600 --> 00:42:12,641
[SPEAKER_00]: So, but I will add that sometimes people don't realize how long development takes, right.

444
00:42:12,981 --> 00:42:19,423
[SPEAKER_00]: From the length of, from the time that somebody thinks they're thinking about building a building and they start to investigate, like,

445
00:42:19,903 --> 00:42:24,666
[SPEAKER_00]: the location, like we're talking like these large lab buildings, residential, not a house, right?

446
00:42:24,686 --> 00:42:37,174
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm not talking about an individual house, but the larger buildings, it takes years to acquire the property, do your due diligence, do your zoning, get your plan, like your zoning things.

447
00:42:38,574 --> 00:42:43,237
[SPEAKER_00]: We are not even broken ground on projects that started talking to us in 2020.

448
00:42:44,901 --> 00:42:56,576
[SPEAKER_00]: submitted applications, started to do their zoning and planning, got permissions from the boards, are now getting building permits to get ready to start to do construction.

449
00:42:57,097 --> 00:42:58,599
[SPEAKER_00]: It can take years.

450
00:42:59,039 --> 00:43:02,884
[SPEAKER_00]: So then you want those buildings to then open and say, look, this works.

451
00:43:03,545 --> 00:43:03,825
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

452
00:43:03,965 --> 00:43:10,369
[SPEAKER_00]: And so you need somebody to actually go through that whole process could easily take three to five years.

453
00:43:11,770 --> 00:43:20,676
[SPEAKER_08]: So is there some way to is there some way to to as and as you point out, this is a long term process.

454
00:43:20,776 --> 00:43:20,996
[SPEAKER_08]: Right.

455
00:43:21,036 --> 00:43:25,319
[SPEAKER_08]: So it it requires people to have a great deal of foresight in terms of where you

456
00:43:26,019 --> 00:43:26,700
[SPEAKER_08]: do things, right?

457
00:43:26,820 --> 00:43:43,976
[SPEAKER_08]: But you see that the challenge that we have as people on this committee is to balance those long term projects with the immediacy that climate resilience requires.

458
00:43:44,597 --> 00:43:50,563
[SPEAKER_08]: And so is there some way that the city can negotiate that interface?

459
00:43:53,427 --> 00:44:10,261
[SPEAKER_05]: If I can jump in, I don't think you can negotiate one-on-one with developers or property owners to do something that's not part of the code, unless you put it into some development guidelines.

460
00:44:10,682 --> 00:44:14,825
[SPEAKER_05]: I would also say I would disagree with Luke, which I rarely do.

461
00:44:14,845 --> 00:44:18,348
[SPEAKER_05]: I think three years is a very short time.

462
00:44:19,281 --> 00:44:30,194
[SPEAKER_05]: both in terms of the development cycle and in terms of the cycle of engineers, design engineers and construction firms and

463
00:44:31,273 --> 00:44:43,475
[SPEAKER_05]: HVAC equipment fabricators and so forth, getting going, getting the capacity that they need to implement something like major net zero buildings.

464
00:44:43,615 --> 00:44:46,956
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think three years is not a long time.

465
00:44:47,756 --> 00:44:48,076
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

466
00:44:48,216 --> 00:44:52,997
[SPEAKER_10]: You're pushing my thought, actually, because I said it may seem like a long time, but.

467
00:44:55,397 --> 00:44:59,738
[SPEAKER_08]: OK, so you think five years would be a more approachable thing for this?

468
00:45:03,127 --> 00:45:09,611
[SPEAKER_10]: keep in mind that we are going to be making significant changes.

469
00:45:10,331 --> 00:45:21,636
[SPEAKER_10]: Significant changes have been made and incentives are also pushing and frankly the communities when a developer comes to a community and they know that the community is

470
00:45:22,857 --> 00:45:30,878
[SPEAKER_10]: pushing for net zero and high performance, the developer does feel that pressure a little bit.

471
00:45:32,119 --> 00:45:36,319
[SPEAKER_10]: And depending on how responsive they are, they may do that.

472
00:45:36,620 --> 00:45:49,362
[SPEAKER_10]: But that is why we have incentives for passive house and things like that to help push this more voluntarily as well as the code that has just been brought in to require it.

473
00:45:50,402 --> 00:45:55,809
[SPEAKER_10]: So I think we have to see how well this is going to work for a little while.

474
00:45:57,971 --> 00:46:05,160
[SPEAKER_10]: And we can keep pushing and it's always good to have public bodies like this one pushing as hard as we can.

475
00:46:06,041 --> 00:46:09,565
[SPEAKER_10]: But we do have to keep some realism as well at the same time.

476
00:46:10,066 --> 00:46:10,166
[SPEAKER_10]: So

477
00:46:11,179 --> 00:46:11,880
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, thanks.

478
00:46:12,360 --> 00:46:12,680
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks.

479
00:46:12,880 --> 00:46:15,102
[SPEAKER_08]: I think that's about all we can devote to that.

