731
01:11:03,242 --> 01:11:04,143
[SPEAKER_11]: except in the summer.

732
01:11:04,824 --> 01:11:08,167
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, I mean, the heat pumps will do your air conditioning in the summer too.

733
01:11:13,011 --> 01:11:17,415
[SPEAKER_06]: Because that's a big component, then it could maybe double the electrical needs.

734
01:11:20,458 --> 01:11:22,020
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, it depends, but yeah.

735
01:11:23,218 --> 01:11:24,499
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, good to know.

736
01:11:25,080 --> 01:11:27,101
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, I might just add in to that.

737
01:11:27,281 --> 01:11:28,842
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, it could double.

738
01:11:29,223 --> 01:11:33,186
[SPEAKER_10]: And again, it comes down to how efficient is your envelope.

739
01:11:34,046 --> 01:11:49,097
[SPEAKER_10]: So if you can take advantage of those air sealing and insulating opportunities as or before you do the heat pump, then you can reduce that energy load, but it'll still depend.

740
01:11:52,591 --> 01:11:53,012
[SPEAKER_02]: Gaston?

741
01:11:55,416 --> 01:11:56,779
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, yeah.

742
01:11:56,799 --> 01:11:57,099
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

743
01:11:57,320 --> 01:11:57,941
[SPEAKER_04]: Quick question.

744
01:11:59,304 --> 01:12:03,732
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, I'm still, from the research that I've done,

745
01:12:04,415 --> 01:12:32,458
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, we're all kind of environment people here, so we have a special kind of motivation to do something like this, but assuming that that wasn't the case, I still don't see why I would convert to a heat pump to heat my house, even if my gas steam boiler went down, because it looks like an efficient way

746
01:12:32,855 --> 01:12:35,377
[SPEAKER_04]: a gas boiler would probably be about 10K.

747
01:12:36,698 --> 01:12:42,062
[SPEAKER_04]: It will be cheaper to run in terms of the, you know, gas versus electricity.

748
01:12:42,082 --> 01:12:44,043
[SPEAKER_04]: It's cheaper to replace.

749
01:12:44,183 --> 01:12:46,144
[SPEAKER_04]: I have all my radiators that work.

750
01:12:46,345 --> 01:12:48,166
[SPEAKER_04]: I have pretty much no maintenance.

751
01:12:48,786 --> 01:12:55,831
[SPEAKER_04]: So why would a regular resident, you know, switch to a heat pump for heating?

752
01:12:55,851 --> 01:13:01,215
[SPEAKER_04]: It wasn't just, you know, trying to be environmentally conscious.

753
01:13:01,837 --> 01:13:09,904
[SPEAKER_04]: And moreover, then, you know, you've got to, even after all the incentives, you still need money to do this.

754
01:13:10,364 --> 01:13:17,009
[SPEAKER_04]: So how, yeah, so how do you sell this to the regular person?

755
01:13:17,170 --> 01:13:27,118
[SPEAKER_04]: And this is not even considering, as I always bring up, landlords, which basically I see no incentives for them to, you know,

756
01:13:28,287 --> 01:13:33,350
[SPEAKER_04]: do anything related to the heating that they offer in their return properties.

757
01:13:34,330 --> 01:13:41,454
[SPEAKER_04]: So do you do anything trying to convince people why they should do this?

758
01:13:43,115 --> 01:13:49,399
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, we don't really try to convince people to do it because we're not trying to do that.

759
01:13:49,479 --> 01:13:57,583
[SPEAKER_11]: But I mean, in general, heat pumps are cheaper than using oil heat.

760
01:13:58,857 --> 01:14:07,921
[SPEAKER_11]: and they're cheaper than using propane and they're cheaper than using old fashioned electric heaters, resistance heaters.

761
01:14:08,802 --> 01:14:16,685
[SPEAKER_11]: So if you've got any of those systems in your house, then it's cheaper to put in heat pumps, right?

762
01:14:16,845 --> 01:14:20,007
[SPEAKER_11]: Although, you know, that makes those numbers.

763
01:14:20,347 --> 01:14:26,890
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, I think I just ran those numbers and they're still true at the moment, even with the increases in electrical and gas.

764
01:14:27,980 --> 01:14:28,460
[SPEAKER_11]: costs.

765
01:14:29,521 --> 01:14:39,746
[SPEAKER_11]: Um, if you've got natural gas or gas, um, it's going to be cheaper to use gas, at least for the moment.

766
01:14:40,867 --> 01:14:52,173
[SPEAKER_11]: But over time, um, gas price are going to go up and probably over time, the cost of electricity is going to go down.

767
01:14:54,154 --> 01:14:54,274
[SPEAKER_11]: Um,

768
01:14:56,505 --> 01:14:59,966
[SPEAKER_08]: But Mark, why would the cost of electricity go down?

769
01:15:00,046 --> 01:15:09,070
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, I have not in my entire 63 years experienced a lower electricity bill.

770
01:15:09,530 --> 01:15:13,412
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, I'm guessing that the

771
01:15:14,772 --> 01:15:18,356
[SPEAKER_08]: I would have to transit to another universe before I see that.

772
01:15:18,496 --> 01:15:26,504
[SPEAKER_08]: So is that something that you can imagine happening in the future, gas or rather electricity prices coming down?

773
01:15:26,524 --> 01:15:29,127
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, it went up 60% literally here.

774
01:15:29,147 --> 01:15:30,729
[SPEAKER_08]: Right.

775
01:15:30,789 --> 01:15:37,716
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, so remember that this year is a very unusual year, and I'm sure they're going to come down from this year.

776
01:15:39,682 --> 01:15:48,805
[SPEAKER_11]: Because a lot of what's going on this year is that Europe is consuming a lot of the US's gas because of the war in Ukraine.

777
01:15:50,586 --> 01:15:52,866
[SPEAKER_11]: And that's probably going to change somewhat.

778
01:15:55,327 --> 01:15:57,248
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, I guess you're right.

779
01:15:57,328 --> 01:16:00,488
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't have a reason to claim that the cost of electricity is going to come down.

780
01:16:07,293 --> 01:16:28,884
[SPEAKER_11]: besides the cost of it coming down, if you insulate your house well and air seal your house so that you don't use that much heat, then the increased costs from electricity may not be that much.

781
01:16:30,245 --> 01:16:32,586
[SPEAKER_11]: And we can do those calculations for people.

782
01:16:40,776 --> 01:16:42,277
[SPEAKER_11]: So it may not be that much more.

783
01:16:42,977 --> 01:16:50,943
[SPEAKER_11]: And frankly, Gaston, most of the people who want to do this are doing it in order to reduce their greenhouse gas emissions.

784
01:16:54,425 --> 01:16:56,867
[SPEAKER_08]: So are you saying education is a big part of it?

785
01:16:58,288 --> 01:17:05,173
[SPEAKER_08]: And getting folks to understand the calamity we're facing is probably

786
01:17:06,318 --> 01:17:15,422
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, well, we're not really we're it's as T pump coaches, we're not trying to show that education, of course, people come to us having understood it already.

787
01:17:15,782 --> 01:17:17,023
[SPEAKER_11]: Sure.

788
01:17:17,063 --> 01:17:23,605
[SPEAKER_11]: But people are trying to get more information about how they do it and what the risks are, and what the costs will be.

789
01:17:23,625 --> 01:17:24,886
[SPEAKER_08]: Sure.

790
01:17:25,506 --> 01:17:27,047
[SPEAKER_11]: And we can help them figure that out.

791
01:17:29,488 --> 01:17:32,249
[SPEAKER_11]: So I mean, just to give you an example of the cost.

792
01:17:33,149 --> 01:17:34,490
[SPEAKER_02]: So I have one

793
01:17:37,318 --> 01:17:47,445
[SPEAKER_11]: client who has gas heat and their boiler is over 30 years old.

794
01:17:49,086 --> 01:17:51,047
[SPEAKER_11]: So they are going to have to replace it sometime.

795
01:17:52,808 --> 01:18:00,113
[SPEAKER_11]: And for whatever reasons that I don't quite understand, their heating costs are fairly low currently.

796
01:18:00,913 --> 01:18:04,776
[SPEAKER_11]: They're only spending like last year and they'll go up this year.

797
01:18:05,324 --> 01:18:06,945
[SPEAKER_11]: you only spent like $1,000 a year on heat.

798
01:18:06,985 --> 01:18:11,188
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, that's my case.

799
01:18:11,248 --> 01:18:13,469
[SPEAKER_04]: So my wallet is even older than that.

800
01:18:13,609 --> 01:18:15,830
[SPEAKER_04]: And I probably spent less than $1,000.

801
01:18:16,491 --> 01:18:18,872
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, granted, I keep my house at 55.

802
01:18:20,093 --> 01:18:23,075
[SPEAKER_04]: But yeah, I mean, I pay almost nothing in heat.

803
01:18:23,535 --> 01:18:23,775
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

804
01:18:23,995 --> 01:18:25,657
[SPEAKER_04]: So please keep going because I'm very interested.

805
01:18:26,337 --> 01:18:26,577
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

806
01:18:26,777 --> 01:18:33,541
[SPEAKER_11]: So if you suppose that switching to heat pumps will make your costs go up by 30%,

807
01:18:35,938 --> 01:18:37,598
[SPEAKER_11]: which is a reasonable approximation.

808
01:18:37,618 --> 01:18:41,279
[SPEAKER_11]: That means your heating bills are only going to go up by $300 a year.

809
01:18:43,360 --> 01:18:49,261
[SPEAKER_11]: And for a lot of people, not everybody, of course, but for a lot of people, that's a cost that they're willing to pay.

810
01:18:51,902 --> 01:18:55,703
[SPEAKER_11]: And then there's another thing, which is a lot of people want to put in air conditioning.

811
01:18:57,323 --> 01:18:59,964
[SPEAKER_11]: And a lot of people want to get rid of their window air conditioners.

812
01:19:01,564 --> 01:19:04,165
[SPEAKER_11]: And they're tired of putting them in and taking them out every year.

813
01:19:05,823 --> 01:19:16,847
[SPEAKER_11]: So if you're thinking about the initial cost of putting in the heat pumps, a lot of people are considering both the cost of the heating equipment and the cost of putting in central air.

814
01:19:17,887 --> 01:19:19,128
[SPEAKER_11]: And it replaces both of them.

815
01:19:27,042 --> 01:19:27,642
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay.

816
01:19:28,043 --> 01:19:32,465
[SPEAKER_06]: Any other questions for Mark before we transition to another item in the agenda then?

817
01:19:32,485 --> 01:19:51,595
[SPEAKER_07]: I have a different type of question, which is just the sense that, and I don't think that heat pumps are a bad idea.

818
01:19:51,695 --> 01:19:53,416
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, I've considered it.

819
01:19:53,456 --> 01:19:55,176
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think it's economic for me, but,

820
01:19:56,840 --> 01:20:12,591
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think they're a bad idea, but I do think that in some way they're putting the cart before the horse or the cart before the horses, the horses being tightening the building envelope and decarbonizing the grid.

821
01:20:13,972 --> 01:20:14,633
[SPEAKER_07]: Because

822
01:20:16,573 --> 01:20:23,947
[SPEAKER_07]: And people would rather, if they can afford it, buy themselves a sexy toy than

823
01:20:27,168 --> 01:20:47,397
[SPEAKER_07]: tighten up their house, which is, you know, there's just no cachet there or trying to deal with the difficult political issue of trying to force the utilities to more rapidly increase the renewable portfolio standard.

824
01:20:48,538 --> 01:20:56,709
[SPEAKER_07]: And until we do that, the heat pumps are consuming gas and oil-produced electricity.

825
01:20:57,550 --> 01:21:04,840
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think that we've got to put the horses in front of the cart.

826
01:21:08,063 --> 01:21:09,204
[SPEAKER_11]: I respond to that.

827
01:21:09,765 --> 01:21:14,508
[SPEAKER_10]: Oh, I do want to just throw in I agree completely with Barry, I would just note.

828
01:21:17,150 --> 01:21:20,553
[SPEAKER_10]: There may be less electric less gas use.

829
01:21:21,594 --> 01:21:27,078
[SPEAKER_10]: If it is centrally produced, not not guaranteed but that is a possibility.

830
01:21:27,559 --> 01:21:27,819
[SPEAKER_10]: Sorry.

831
01:21:28,680 --> 01:21:29,820
[SPEAKER_08]: You mean as opposed to.

832
01:21:31,920 --> 01:21:42,207
[SPEAKER_10]: Consumed in each house, no, as opposed to delivery to each house along the way, and the gas lines to each house, et cetera.

833
01:21:42,507 --> 01:21:48,951
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, so if it's centrally produced and there'd be a central heater, is that what you're looking for?

834
01:21:49,091 --> 01:21:56,396
[SPEAKER_10]: No, centrally produced electricity as opposed to heating via fossil fuel in each house.

835
01:22:00,345 --> 01:22:04,947
[SPEAKER_07]: but you also get transmission and distribution losses, but I would like to hear.

836
01:22:05,127 --> 01:22:06,828
[SPEAKER_11]: Barry, let me respond to that.

837
01:22:09,189 --> 01:22:19,394
[SPEAKER_11]: One is that according to Mass Save, you have to make your house efficient before they will let you get rebates.

838
01:22:20,334 --> 01:22:27,638
[SPEAKER_11]: So you have to get an audit, you have to put in insulation, and you have to tighten up your home.

839
01:22:28,953 --> 01:22:32,316
[SPEAKER_11]: and you can't get the rebate until you've done that.

840
01:22:32,356 --> 01:22:38,101
[SPEAKER_11]: So they are putting the horse before the cart there.

841
01:22:39,022 --> 01:22:40,863
[SPEAKER_11]: One of the two horses, yeah.

842
01:22:41,244 --> 01:22:55,936
[SPEAKER_11]: And secondly, as far as the grid, so right now the grid is somewhat cleaner than using just gas because the grid has some solar in it, it has some wind in it, and frankly, it's got some nukes in it.

843
01:22:57,167 --> 01:23:04,290
[SPEAKER_11]: So if you, depends whether you like nukes or not, but the grid is somewhat cleaner than using just gas directly right now.

844
01:23:05,190 --> 01:23:10,872
[SPEAKER_11]: And because the RPS is going up every year, the grid is going to get cleaner year by year.

845
01:23:13,613 --> 01:23:14,433
[SPEAKER_11]: It's just going to.

846
01:23:16,794 --> 01:23:20,275
[SPEAKER_11]: And so we're kind of, I think we're trying to do both sides at once.

847
01:23:20,996 --> 01:23:24,677
[SPEAKER_11]: So cleaning up the grid is cleaning up the supply of fuel.

848
01:23:26,118 --> 01:23:29,901
[SPEAKER_11]: putting in heat pumps is cleaning up the demand, right?

849
01:23:30,401 --> 01:23:32,663
[SPEAKER_11]: And you need to do both things at the same time.

850
01:23:33,923 --> 01:23:50,415
[SPEAKER_11]: And particularly for heat pumps, it's important to do it now because everybody who's trying to replace their heat pump, who's trying to replace their heating system currently, if they've got a 25, 30 year old or older system,

851
01:23:54,930 --> 01:24:02,456
[SPEAKER_11]: Well, if they put in that system now, they're likely to still have it in 2050, right?

852
01:24:03,337 --> 01:24:10,702
[SPEAKER_11]: So we need to get people to switch into heat pumps when they're switching, when they're putting in new heating systems currently.

853
01:24:13,545 --> 01:24:23,793
[SPEAKER_11]: So we're not arguing necessarily that it makes sense for everybody to do it now, if they've got a relatively new gas system, but if you got one that's old,

854
01:24:24,559 --> 01:24:25,781
[SPEAKER_11]: then it may make sense to do it.

855
01:24:28,044 --> 01:24:33,632
[SPEAKER_08]: So more of a replacement and inclusion in new buildings and stuff.

856
01:24:35,935 --> 01:24:40,141
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, and a lot of people have old gas furnaces or gas boilers.

857
01:24:40,621 --> 01:24:41,803
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, I do.

858
01:24:45,544 --> 01:24:47,065
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm done with my presentation.

859
01:24:47,165 --> 01:24:50,306
[SPEAKER_06]: If anyone has any more questions for Mark.

860
01:24:51,627 --> 01:24:54,028
[SPEAKER_04]: I just have two very quick comments.

861
01:24:54,048 --> 01:25:04,673
[SPEAKER_04]: So the first one is that even though I agree with everything that Luke and Marta had said in terms of getting rid of fossil fuels, the pilot to get rid of fossil fuels for new construction.

862
01:25:06,050 --> 01:25:26,300
[SPEAKER_04]: To me, it's a no brainer that that's where we should be pushing this it's for you know either hold renovations or new houses to me like I don't see how a lab or an industry is different, but for residential or even commercial I don't see why we should have new residential and commercial properties that are not fully electric number one.

863
01:25:27,098 --> 01:25:40,902
[SPEAKER_04]: And number two, that I would like to see, so this goes into the next section, session two that we're going to cover, but it will be interesting to see because I'm still dubious, you know, so if I replace all of my system with a heat pump, what do I do with my radiator?

864
01:25:40,982 --> 01:25:44,462
[SPEAKER_04]: What do I do with all the pipes and stuff that, you know, feed the radiator?

865
01:25:44,522 --> 01:25:45,503
[SPEAKER_04]: What do I do with all of that?

866
01:25:45,603 --> 01:25:46,523
[SPEAKER_04]: I would have to move out.

867
01:25:47,112 --> 01:25:49,774
[SPEAKER_04]: break all the walls, get rid of all of that, et cetera.

868
01:25:49,794 --> 01:25:53,277
[SPEAKER_04]: So in addition to it being a lot of money, it's like a big project.

869
01:25:53,317 --> 01:26:09,171
[SPEAKER_04]: So I'm also curious for the future, not right now, to discuss at which point does it become sort of better to maybe, you know, just leave the house how it is and then, you know, maybe sell it and then move to a new one that is like, you know, passive sort of thing, new construction.

870
01:26:09,211 --> 01:26:11,633
[SPEAKER_04]: But also like, you know, how expensive is it, for example,

871
01:26:12,386 --> 01:26:18,291
[SPEAKER_04]: a retrofit, a deep energy retrofit, as opposed to just like, you know, knocking down the house and building it from scratch.

872
01:26:18,311 --> 01:26:24,937
[SPEAKER_04]: So for future discussion, I will be waiting to see Luke or someone that knows about this to sort of address this.

873
01:26:25,157 --> 01:26:26,338
[SPEAKER_04]: But this was extremely interesting.

874
01:26:26,358 --> 01:26:29,681
[SPEAKER_04]: So thank you so much, Mark and Bob for presenting.

875
01:26:29,781 --> 01:26:30,442
[SPEAKER_04]: I really appreciate it.

876
01:26:30,827 --> 01:26:31,287
[SPEAKER_08]: Absolutely.

877
