879
01:26:34,490 --> 01:26:38,914
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks so much, Mark, for chiming in and giving us details about that.

880
01:26:40,576 --> 01:26:43,278
[SPEAKER_08]: And I completely agree with Gaston.

881
01:26:45,540 --> 01:26:53,987
[SPEAKER_08]: There is already existing infrastructure that you have to refurbish or get rid of completely in order to install the new stuff.

882
01:26:55,648 --> 01:27:07,412
[SPEAKER_08]: what information isn't there is, in my mind anyway, is how you can save energy with your old shitty system that you have in place.

883
01:27:07,892 --> 01:27:18,516
[SPEAKER_08]: Like, you know, there's one thing that came to my mind when I moved into this house was, well, it might be a good idea to clean the radiators so that water actually

884
01:27:19,758 --> 01:27:23,500
[SPEAKER_08]: goes into the fanning sections.

885
01:27:23,700 --> 01:27:27,462
[SPEAKER_08]: And that would be a lot more efficient.

886
01:27:27,542 --> 01:27:37,728
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, I go around and I have one right here with a little key opening up the air thing for the radiators so that air pops out.

887
01:27:37,848 --> 01:27:41,530
[SPEAKER_08]: And I hope that water would replace that air.

888
01:27:41,671 --> 01:27:42,651
[SPEAKER_08]: Things like that.

889
01:27:47,130 --> 01:27:54,453
[SPEAKER_08]: don't really configure in the energy efficiency kind of dialogue and discourse we have.

890
01:27:54,913 --> 01:27:57,934
[SPEAKER_08]: So I applaud Gaston for bringing that up.

891
01:27:58,054 --> 01:27:59,795
[SPEAKER_08]: Very, very important topic.

